(44, 23, 3, 3, 19, 35, 35, 'judge me after the law', 'Judgment and Righteousness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of unrighteous judgment. Paul''s accusation of being judged contrary to the law resonates with the call for righteousness in judgment found in Leviticus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 3, 19, 58, 1, 2, 'judge me after the law', 'Judgment and Wickedness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of unjust judgment. Both passages emphasize the idea of judging contrary to righteousness, with Acts 23:3 referencing a wrongful judgment and Psalms 58:1-2 questioning the integrity of judgment among men.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 3, 19, 82, 1, 2, 'judge me after the law', 'Judgment and Injustice Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of unjust judgment present in both passages. Paul accuses the high priest of judging him contrary to the law, paralleling the call in Psalms to judge justly and not accept the persons of the wicked.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 5, 2, 22, 28, 28, 'Thou shalt not speak evil of the ruler of thy people.', 'Connection of Rulers in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the prohibition against speaking ill of leaders. Acts 23:5 directly quotes the principle found in Exodus 22:28 regarding rulers of the people.', 'quotation', 0.503, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 5, 21, 10, 20, 20, 'Thou shalt not speak evil of the ruler of thy people', 'Respect for Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of refraining from speaking ill of rulers. Both passages emphasize the importance of respecting authority figures, whether in public or private thoughts.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 5, 65, 1, 8, 9, 'Thou shalt not speak evil of the ruler of thy people', 'Respect for Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of not speaking evil against authority figures. Both passages emphasize the importance of showing respect towards dignities and rulers, as seen in Paul''s reference to the high priest and Michael''s restraint against the devil.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 5, 61, 2, 10, 10, 'Thou shalt not speak evil of the ruler of thy people', 'Connection on Speaking Evil of Rulers', 'This connection highlights the theme of speaking against authority. Both passages emphasize the importance of respecting rulers and the consequences of despising government.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 5, 44, 24, 17, 17, 'ruler of thy people', 'Connection of Leadership and Offerings', 'This connection highlights the theme of respect for authority and the act of bringing offerings. In Acts 23:5, Paul acknowledges the ruler''s position, while in Acts 24:17, he speaks of bringing alms to his nation, suggesting a relationship between leadership and communal support.', 'theme', 0.244, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 6, 44, 24, 15, 15, 'resurrection of the dead', 'Resurrection of the Dead', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of resurrection, with Paul identifying himself as a Pharisee who believes in it and expressing hope in a future resurrection. This thematic connection underscores the shared belief in resurrection among different Jewish groups.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 6, 44, 24, 21, 21, 'resurrection of the dead', 'Connection on Resurrection of the Dead', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of resurrection, with Paul explicitly stating he is called in question regarding it. This connection highlights the continuity of Paul''s defense centered on the resurrection across different contexts.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 6, 50, 3, 5, 5, 'I am a Pharisee', 'Paul''s Identity as a Pharisee', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s identity as a Pharisee, highlighting his background and beliefs. In Acts, he identifies himself as a Pharisee in relation to the resurrection, while in Philippians, he states his lineage and adherence to the law as a Pharisee.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 6, 40, 22, 23, 23, 'resurrection of the dead', 'Resurrection Debate Between Groups', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of resurrection, with Acts highlighting Paul''s identity as a Pharisee who believes in it, while Matthew presents the Sadducees who deny it. This connection highlights the theological divide between the two groups regarding the resurrection.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 6, 40, 10, 16, 16, 'the hope and resurrection of the dead', 'Wisdom in Adversity', 'This connection highlights the theme of navigating conflict. Paul identifies himself among opposing groups, demonstrating wisdom in a challenging situation, similar to being ''wise as serpents'' in the face of danger.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 7, 19, 55, 9, 9, NULL, 'Division and Strife in Context', 'Both passages emphasize division and conflict among people. Acts 23:7 describes a division between the Pharisees and Sadducees, while Psalms 55:9 calls for the destruction of tongues due to violence and strife.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 7, 40, 10, 34, 34, 'dissension between the Pharisees and the Sadducees', 'Division and Conflict in Teachings', 'This connection highlights the theme of division present in both passages. Acts 23:7 describes a dissension, while Matthew 10:34 speaks of bringing a sword, indicating conflict rather than peace.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 7, 43, 7, 40, 43, 'there arose a dissension', 'Division Among the People', 'Both passages emphasize division among the people. In Acts, the dissension arises between the Pharisees and Sadducees, while in John, the crowd is divided over Jesus'' identity.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 7, 44, 14, 4, 4, 'the multitude was divided', 'Division Among Groups', 'Both passages emphasize division within groups, highlighting conflict among differing beliefs. In Acts 23:7, the dissension arises between the Pharisees and Sadducees, while in Acts 14:4, the multitude is divided between Jews and apostles.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 8, 42, 20, 27, 27, NULL, 'Sadducees and Resurrection Denial', 'Both passages emphasize the Sadducees'' denial of resurrection. Acts 23:8 states that the Sadducees say there is no resurrection, which is echoed in Luke 20:27 where they are described as denying any resurrection.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 8, 40, 22, 23, 23, NULL, 'Sadducees and Resurrection Beliefs', 'Both passages emphasize the Sadducees'' denial of resurrection. Acts 23:8 explicitly states their belief, while Matthew 22:23 introduces them with the same claim.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 8, 41, 12, 18, 18, 'there is no resurrection', 'Sadducees and Resurrection Beliefs', 'Both passages emphasize the Sadducees'' denial of resurrection. Acts 23:8 states their belief that there is ''no resurrection,'' which is echoed in Mark 12:18. This connection highlights the consistent portrayal of Sadducean theology.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 8, 44, 4, 1, 1, 'no resurrection', 'Sadducees and Resurrection Beliefs', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Sadducees in relation to resurrection beliefs. Acts 23:8 states the Sadducees deny resurrection, while Acts 4:1 shows their presence opposing the apostles.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 9, 44, 22, 7, 7, 'if a spirit or an angel', 'Divine Communication and Persecution', 'Both passages emphasize a divine voice speaking to Saul. The mention of a spirit or angel in Acts 23:9 connects to the voice Saul hears in Acts 22:7, highlighting the theme of divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 9, 44, 22, 17, 18, 'if a spirit or an angel', 'Divine Communication and Response', 'Both passages emphasize divine communication, with Acts 22:17-18 describing a vision from God and Acts 23:9 referencing a spirit or angel. This connection highlights the theme of responding to divine messages, suggesting a continuity in the experience of revelation.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 9, 43, 12, 29, 29, NULL, 'Divine Communication Through Angels', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine communication through angels. Both passages mention the idea of an angel speaking, suggesting a shared understanding of spiritual encounters.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 9, 20, 16, 7, 7, 'let us not fight against God', 'Peace with Enemies', 'This connection highlights how divine approval can lead to unexpected harmony, as seen in both passages. In Acts, the Pharisees acknowledge that opposing Paul could mean fighting against God, suggesting that pleasing God can influence even adversaries. Similarly, Proverbs states that when a man''s ways please the Lord, his enemies may be at peace.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 9, 41, 2, 16, 16, NULL, 'Conflict with Religious Authorities', 'Both passages emphasize the opposition faced by Jesus from religious leaders. In Acts, the Pharisees defend Paul against accusations, while in Mark, they criticize Jesus for associating with sinners.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 9, 9, 24, 17, 17, 'let us not fight against God', 'Righteousness and Divine Communication', 'This connection highlights the theme of righteousness in both passages. In Acts, the Pharisees acknowledge a divine communication, while in 1 Samuel, David is recognized as more righteous despite being wronged.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 9, 42, 5, 30, 30, 'scribes that were of the Phariseesâ€™ part', 'Conflict with Scribes and Pharisees', 'This connection highlights the opposition faced by both Paul and Jesus from the Pharisees and their scribes. In Acts, the Pharisees defend Paul against accusations, while in Luke, they criticize Jesus for associating with sinners.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 10, 44, 22, 24, 24, NULL, 'Connection Between Paul''s Arrest', 'Both passages emphasize the chief captain''s actions to protect Paul. In Acts 22:24, he commands Paul to be brought into the castle, while in Acts 23:10, he orders soldiers to take him by force to ensure his safety.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 23, 10, 59, 1, 19, 19, 'great dissension', 'Listening and Responding in Conflict', 'This connection highlights the importance of being ''swift to hear'' in situations of dissension, as seen in both passages. Acts 23:10 describes a chaotic moment where listening and understanding could prevent escalation, while James 1:19 advises a measured response to conflict.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
